\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bob Ainsworth]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Whip of the Labour Party|Labour Deputy Chief Whip]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]|years=2007\u20142008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tommy McAvoy]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Geoff Hoon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Whip of the Labour Party|Labour Chief Whip]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]|years=2008\u20142010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rosie Winterton]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rosie Winterton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Whip of the Labour Party|Labour Chief Whip]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]|years=2016\u2014present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Blair Cabinet}}\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{North East Labour Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Nick}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Agriculture ministers of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:English humanists]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:LGBT members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Israel]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Tunbridge Wells Grammar School for Boys]]\n[[Category:People from Hawkhurst]]\n[[Category:Treasurers of the Household]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = Nick Brown\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n|image            = Official portrait of Rt Hon Nicholas Brown MP crop 2.jpg\n|caption = Brown in 2020\n|office           = [[Chief Whip|Opposition Chief Whip]] of the [[House of Commons]]\n|leader           = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]<br />[[Keir Starmer]]\n|term_start       = 6 October 2016\n|term_end         = \n|predecessor      = [[Rosie Winterton]]\n|successor        = \n|leader1          = [[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}<br />[[Ed Miliband]]\n|term_start1      = 11 May 2010\n|term_end1        = 7 October 2010\n|predecessor1     = [[Patrick McLoughlin]]\n|successor1       = [[Rosie Winterton]]\n|office2          = [[Chief Whip|Chief Whip of the House of Commons]]<br />[[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]]\n|primeminister2   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start2      = 3 October 2008\n|term_end2        = 11 May 2010\n|predecessor2     = [[Geoff Hoon]]\n|successor2       = [[Patrick McLoughlin]]\n|primeminister3   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start3      = 2 May 1997\n|term_end3        = 27 July 1998\n|predecessor3     = [[Alastair Goodlad]]\n|successor3       = [[Ann Taylor, Baroness Taylor of Bolton|Ann Taylor]]\n|office4          = [[Regional minister|Minister for the North East]]\n|primeminister4   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start4      = 28 June 2007\n|term_end4        = 11 May 2010\n|predecessor4     = Position established \n|successor4       = Position abolished\n|office5          = [[Chief Whip|Deputy Chief Whip of the Government]]<br />[[Treasurer of the Household]]\n|primeminister5   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start5      = 28 June 2007\n|term_end5        = 3 October 2008\n|predecessor5     = [[Bob Ainsworth]]\n|successor5       = [[Tommy McAvoy]]\n|office6          = [[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister of State for Work]]\n|primeminister6   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start6      = 11 June 2001\n|term_end6        = 13 June 2003\n|predecessor6     = Position established\n|successor6       = [[Des Browne]]\n|office7          = [[Minister of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]]\n|primeminister7   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start7      = 27 July 1998\n|term_end7        = 11 June 2001\n|predecessor7     = [[Jack Cunningham, Baron Cunningham of Felling|Jack Cunningham]]\n|successor7       = [[Margaret Beckett]] {{small|([[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]])}}\n|office8          = [[Shadow Leader of the House of Commons]]<br />{{small|Acting}}\n|leader8          = [[Margaret Beckett]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n|term_start8      = 12 May 1994\n|term_end8        = 21 July 1994\n|predecessor8     = [[Margaret Beckett]]\n|successor8       = [[Margaret Beckett]]\n|office9          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Newcastle upon Tyne East (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle upon Tyne East]]<br />{{small|[[Newcastle upon Tyne East and Wallsend (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle upon Tyne East and Wallsend]] (1997\u20132010)}}\n|term_start9      = 9 June 1983\n|term_end9        = \n|predecessor9     = [[Mike Thomas (politician)|Mike Thomas]]\n|successor9       = \n|majority9        = 15,463 (35.7%)\n|birth_name       = Nicholas Hugh Brown\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1950|6|13|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Hawkhurst]], [[England]], UK\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|alma_mater       = [[University of Manchester]]\n|website          = {{url|nickbrownmp.com|Official website}}<br />\n}}\n'''Nicholas Hugh Brown'''<ref name=\"freeman\">{{cite web |url=http://www.newcastle.gov.uk/your-council/lord-mayor/honorary-freedom-citations#nbrownmp |title=Honorary Freemen |publisher=Newcastle.gov.uk |date=14 December 2017 |accessdate=8 January 2019 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Gc945WSy?url=http://www.newcastle.gov.uk/your-council/lord-mayor/honorary-freedom-citations#nbrownmp |archive-date=14 May 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> (born 13 June 1950) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Newcastle upon Tyne East (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle upon Tyne East]] since [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] and has served as [[Chief Whip|Opposition Chief Whip]] of the [[House of Commons]] in the [[Shadow Cabinet]]s of [[Jeremy Corbyn]] and [[Keir Starmer]] since 2016. He also serves the Labour Party as their [[Chief Whip]], and has held this role for three separate terms, during the Labour Party\u2019s time both in government and in opposition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.number10.gov.uk/Page17065 |title=Number 10 Press release |publisher=Number10.gov.uk |accessdate=29 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100125122712/http://www.number10.gov.uk/Page17065 |archivedate=25 January 2010  }}</ref> Brown held several ministerial positions in the governments of [[Blair ministry|Blair]] and [[Brown ministry|Brown]].\n\n==Early life==\nBrown was born in [[Hawkhurst]], [[Kent]], and brought up in nearby [[Royal Tunbridge Wells|Tunbridge Wells]], attending [[Tunbridge Wells Grammar School for Boys]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Newcastle+upon+Tyne+East/Nicholas+Brown |title=Nicholas Brown - Parliamentary candidates |publisher=Ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk |date= |accessdate=29 February 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120801134332/http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Newcastle+upon+Tyne+East/Nicholas+Brown |archive-date=1 August 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> before studying at the [[University of Manchester]]. After graduating, he worked in advertising for [[Procter & Gamble]], but in 1978 he moved to be legal adviser to the Northern Region of the [[GMB (trade union)|GMBATU]], based in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]]. In 1980 he was elected to [[Newcastle City Council]], representing Walker ward. His role in the union gave him a role in maximising the union's influence in [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] selections.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n==Political career==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=January 2019}}\nWhen [[Mike Thomas (politician)|Mike Thomas]], the sitting Labour [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Newcastle upon Tyne East (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle upon Tyne East]], defected to the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|SDP]], Brown was chosen as the new Labour Party candidate for the seat, easily retaining it for Labour at the 1983 general election. He joined Labour's front bench in 1985 as a spokesman on Legal Affairs; from 1988 he was a Treasury spokesman and from 1994 he shadowed Health.\n\nOriginally elected to the Commons in the same year as [[Gordon Brown]] and [[Tony Blair]] he was initially close to both men but over time he became his namesake Brown's staunchest ally, though the two are unrelated. In the [[1994 Labour Party leadership election|1994 Labour leadership election]] he acted as Brown's unofficial campaign manager, and according to [[Gordon Brown]]'s biographer [[Paul Routledge]], advised against him pulling out of the contest in Blair's favour.\n\nIn 1995, he was appointed Deputy Chief Whip and played a central role in the close Parliament in trying to defeat the Conservatives. After Labour's [[1997 United Kingdom general election|election]] victory in 1997, he was appointed [[Chief Whip]], but stayed there only for a year, and was moved to the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]] in 1998. This change, which followed the publication of the Routledge biography earlier that year, was widely seen as a demotion,{{citation needed|date=September 2014}} and ascribed to his close connection with Brown.\n\nHis tenure at MAFF saw several animal health crises ending with the [[2001 United Kingdom foot-and-mouth outbreak|2001 foot-and-mouth outbreak]]. Brown's handling of the outbreak, which some in the media and politics used to attack the government, was criticised, though throughout he maintained the support of the farming and food industries and the veterinary profession.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}} Suggestions that a [[vaccination]] strategy should have been practised in preference to the culling of hundreds of thousands of animals, made with the benefit of hindsight, did not help his cause, and he was demoted out to be the Minister of Work, with non-voting Cabinet rank, at the [[Department for Work and Pensions]] after the general election of 2001. In June 2003, he was dropped from the Government altogether, receiving news of his sacking by [[Tony Blair]] during the course of a party held to mark his 20 years as an MP.\n\nBrown remains closely allied to [[Gordon Brown]]. In 2004 he was one of the organisers of a rebellion over the government's proposals for student finance, but hours before the vote announced that he had received concessions from the Government and would now support it. It was suspected that the Chancellor had ordered him to back down, but the affair cost him some credibility. On 29 June 2007 he was announced as Brown's new Deputy Chief Whip and Minister for the North East. Following a government reshuffle, he was returned to his original government position of Government Chief Whip, retaining his position as Minister for the North East.\n\nIn 2009, Brown was put in charge of investigating questionable expense claims by Labour MPs. According to '' [[The Daily Telegraph]]'', between 2004 and 2008, he himself claimed a total of \u00a387,708 for his constituency home including \u00a318,800 for food. Allowances sought, without submission of receipts, included \u00a3200 a month for repairs, \u00a3200 a month for service and maintenance and \u00a3250 a month for a cleaner.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5346633/MPs-expenses-Nick-Brown-claims-18800-for-food-without-receipts.html|title=MPs' expenses: Nick Brown claims \u00a318,800 for food without receipts|work=The Telegraph|location=London|first1=Gordon|last1=Rayner|first2=Jon|last2=Swaine|date=19 May 2009|access-date=2 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202053137/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5346633/MPs-expenses-Nick-Brown-claims-18800-for-food-without-receipts.html|archive-date=2 February 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBrown's mortgage interest repayments for 2007-8 totalled \u00a36,600, but he also claimed a total of \u00a323,068, just \u00a315 below the maximum allowable amount for the year. The claim included \u00a34,800 for food \u2013 the maximum allowable amount \u2013 \u00a32,880 for repairs and insurance, \u00a32,880 for services, \u00a3897.65 for cleaning, \u00a31,640 for phones and \u00a31,810 for utilities. Brown, however, has said that he saved the taxpayer a considerable amount of money by turning down a Government car and driver upon being made Chief Whip, the annual cost of which would have been around \u00a3100,000.<ref>{{cite news |first=William |last=Green |url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-evening-chronicle/2009/05/12/mps-expenses-north-east-minister-opens-up-72703-23601259/ |title=MPs' expenses: North East Minister opens up |work=Evening Chronicle |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=12 May 2009 |accessdate=29 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105135600/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-evening-chronicle/2009/05/12/mps-expenses-north-east-minister-opens-up-72703-23601259/ |archive-date=5 January 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 29 January 2010, during the [[News of the World phone hacking affair|''News of the World'' phone hacking affair]], Brown said that his landline may have been bugged in an \"amateurish attempt\" in 1998, around the time of his outing.<ref name=\"indy-bugged\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/my-landline-was-bugged-as-papers-tried-to-out-me-says-nick-brown-2197771.html |author= |title=My landline was bugged as papers tried to 'out' me, says Nick Brown |work=The Independent |date=29 January 2011 |accessdate=29 January 2011 |location=London |first=Cahal |last=Milmo |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110129085538/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/my-landline-was-bugged-as-papers-tried-to-out-me-says-nick-brown-2197771.html |archive-date=29 January 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was also contacted by police in the West of England in 2003 who told him that they were pursuing a phone-tapping prosecution and he was one of those who may have been targeted. The case collapsed when it reached court and full details of the allegations were never disclosed. Brown said that: \"Given that it was near [Prince Charles' home] Highgrove, my assumption was that this might involve the Royal Family. But I was never explicitly told that.\"<ref name=\"indy-bugged\"/>\n\nOn 29 September 2010, newly elected Labour Party leader [[Ed Miliband]] asked Brown not to stand for re-election as Opposition Chief Whip due to the need for a \"break from the past\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11436851 |title=Ed Miliband asks chief whip Nick Brown to step aside |work=BBC News |date=29 September 2010 |accessdate=29 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120223114331/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11436851 |archive-date=23 February 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 6 October 2016, Brown was re-appointed Labour Chief Whip, under [[Jeremy Corbyn]], with whom he had an unlikely personal friendship,<ref>\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2016/10/corbynsceptics-watch-out-nick-brown-coming-you |author= |title=Watch out Corbynsceptics, Nick Brown is Coming to Get You |work=The New Statesman |date=13 October 2016 |accessdate=23 January 2019 |location=London |first=Stephen |last=Bush |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327091031/https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2016/10/corbynsceptics-watch-out-nick-brown-coming-you |archive-date=27 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and he went on to play an important role in the Parliamentary debates and votes over [[Brexit]] during 2018 and 2019. This included the largest ever defeat suffered by a government, on Tuesday 15 January 2019. This reappointment means that Brown is the only person to have held the job three times, under three different leaders, and in three different decades. From a position in 1997 of trying to ensure Labour's dissident factions supported Tony Blair's New Labour policies, from 2016 he has been charged with trying to ensure Labour's rebellious Blairites support Jeremy Corbyn's policies.\n\nHe is the chairman of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Speedway racing.\n\nHe is a member of [[Labour Friends of Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lfi.org.uk/in-parliament/|title=LFI Supporters in Parliament|accessdate=8 September 2019|work=Labour Friends of Israel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002100511/https://www.lfi.org.uk/in-parliament/|archive-date=2 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBrown is the holder of the freedom of the City of Newcastle upon Tyne award.<ref name=\"freeman\"/> He is a supporter of [[Humanists UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://humanism.org.uk/about/our-people/patrons/rt-hon-nick-brown-mp/|title=Rt Hon Nick Brown MP|date=22 October 2013|work=humanism.org.uk|access-date=6 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407233308/https://humanism.org.uk/about/our-people/patrons/rt-hon-nick-brown-mp/|archive-date=7 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Brown is also an honorary associate of the National Secular Society.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Secular Society Honorary Associates|url=https://secularism.org.uk/honorary-associates.html|website=National Secular Society|accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref> He is known to have a love for classical music,<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/oct/03/labour.gordonbrown3</ref> which developed during his university years.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.nickbrownmp.com/ Nick Brown MP] official constituency website\n*[http://www.labour.org.uk/maps/locinfo.phtml?ctid=2258 Profile] at the Labour Party{{UK MP links | parliament = mr-nicholas-brown/523 | hansard = mr-nick-brown | hansardcurr = 2330 | guardian = 658/nick-brown | publicwhip = Nick_Brown | theywork = nick_brown | record = Nicholas-Brown/Newcastle-upon-Tyne-East/100 | bbc = 25744.stm | journalisted = nick-brown }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Thomas (politician)|Mike Thomas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Newcastle upon Tyne East and Wallsend (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle upon Tyne East]]<br />{{small|[[Newcastle upon Tyne East and Wallsend (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle upon Tyne East and Wallsend]] ([[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]])}}|years=[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Margaret Beckett]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Leader of the House of Commons]]<br />{{small|Acting}}|years=1994}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Margaret Beckett]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Alastair Goodlad]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Whip]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]|years=1997\u20131998}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Ann Taylor, Baroness Taylor of Bolton|Ann Taylor]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]]|years=1997\u